<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Builder on Henry Techie</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/builder/</link><description>Recent content in Builder on Henry Techie</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 10 May 2025 00:00:00 +0700</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://namanh11611.github.io/tags/builder/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Design Pattern: The Journey of Builder Pattern - from 60 lines of Java to 1 line of Kotlin</title><link>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/</link><pubDate>Sat, 10 May 2025 00:00:00 +0700</pubDate><guid>https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/</guid><description>&lt;img src="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/builder.webp" alt="Featured image of post Design Pattern: The Journey of Builder Pattern - from 60 lines of Java to 1 line of Kotlin" /&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Photo by &lt;a class="link" href="https://unsplash.com/@framesforyourheart?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;amp;utm_source=unsplash" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;Frames For Your Heart&lt;/a&gt; on &lt;a class="link" href="https://unsplash.com/photos/yellow-crane-near-building-during-daytime-VoI2jd75M6Q?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;amp;utm_source=unsplash" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
&gt;Unsplash&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the programming world, &lt;strong&gt;Builder Pattern&lt;/strong&gt; is known as one of the popular design patterns in the &lt;strong&gt;Creational Pattern&lt;/strong&gt; group, helping to create complex objects in a flexible and readable way. You may have encountered it in your code but not noticed. In older programming languages, implementing the &lt;strong&gt;Builder Pattern&lt;/strong&gt; could be lengthy and complicated, but newer languages have made it much easier. Today, let&amp;rsquo;s explore the journey of Builder Pattern from &lt;strong&gt;60 lines of Java code&lt;/strong&gt; to just &lt;strong&gt;1 line in Kotlin&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1 id="what-is-the-builder-pattern"&gt;What is the Builder Pattern?
&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;In software development, there are many classes that need to be initialized with various properties. For example, a &lt;code&gt;House&lt;/code&gt; class might have properties like &lt;code&gt;wall&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;door&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;window&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;roof&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;garage&lt;/code&gt;&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Normally, to initialize an instance of this class, you might write:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;div class="chroma"&gt;
&lt;table class="lntable"&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class="lntd"&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code&gt;&lt;span class="lnt"&gt;1
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td class="lntd"&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-java" data-lang="java"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;House&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;myHouse&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="o"&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="k"&gt;new&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;House&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;4&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="n"&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="p"&gt;);&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="w"&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Reading this code, you might wonder what &lt;code&gt;4&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;2&lt;/code&gt; mean. If you use a regular constructor or setters for each property, you may encounter issues like:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hard to read and easy to confuse&lt;/strong&gt;: Calling a constructor with many parameters without knowing their meaning can be confusing.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Prone to errors&lt;/strong&gt;: If the order of parameters is wrong, the compiler may not catch it if the parameters have the same type.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lack of flexibility&lt;/strong&gt;: If some properties are optional, you&amp;rsquo;ll need many overloaded constructors or setters, making the code messy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Risk of creating objects in an invalid state&lt;/strong&gt;: If not all necessary setters are called, the object may lack required data.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s why the &lt;strong&gt;Builder Pattern&lt;/strong&gt; was created to solve these problems by moving the code for initializing properties out of the class and into another class called the &lt;strong&gt;Builder&lt;/strong&gt;. You can see the illustration below:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/house_builder.webp"
width="410"
height="280"
srcset="https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/house_builder_hu_1a2ff973ef95520.webp 480w, https://namanh11611.github.io/p/design-pattern-builder/house_builder_hu_2d4f6d0f38000527.webp 1024w"
loading="lazy"
alt="Builder"
class="gallery-image"
data-flex-grow="146"
data-flex-basis="351px"
&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Separating the code into &lt;code&gt;HouseBuilder&lt;/code&gt; allows you to create objects step by step, clearly and flexibly. You can choose which properties to set and which to skip.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let&amp;rsquo;s look at the implementation in &lt;strong&gt;Java&lt;/strong&gt; next.&lt;/p&gt;
